To resolve the issue of having multiple Redis configurations and injecting the corresponding Redis templates, you can use the **@Qualifier** annotation to specify which Redis template should be injected in each case. Here&#39;s how you can modify your code to achieve this:

Update the TokenRedisConfiguration class:


    @Configuration
    public class TokenRedisConfiguration {
    
        // ...
    
        @Bean
        @Qualifier(&quot;tokenRedisTemplate&quot;)
        public RedisTemplate&lt;String, Token&gt; tokenRedisTemplate(
                @Qualifier(&quot;tokenRedisFactory&quot;) LettuceConnectionFactory tokenRedisFactory
        ) {
            RedisTemplate&lt;String, Token&gt; redisTemplate = new RedisTemplate&lt;&gt;();
            redisTemplate.setConnectionFactory(tokenRedisFactory);
            // Configure RedisTemplate
            // ...
            return redisTemplate;
        }
    
    }

Update the InvoiceRedisConfiguration class:


    @Configuration
    public class InvoiceRedisConfiguration {
    
        // ...
    
        @Bean
        @Qualifier(&quot;invoiceRedisTemplate&quot;)
        public RedisTemplate&lt;String, Invoice&gt; invoiceRedisTemplate(
                @Qualifier(&quot;invoiceRedisFactory&quot;) LettuceConnectionFactory invoiceRedisFactory
        ) {
            RedisTemplate&lt;String, Invoice&gt; redisTemplate = new RedisTemplate&lt;&gt;();
            redisTemplate.setConnectionFactory(invoiceRedisFactory);
            // Configure RedisTemplate
            // ...
            return redisTemplate;
        }
    
    }

In your controller or middleware classes, inject the Redis templates using the @Qualifier annotation:


    @RestController
    public class MyController {
    
        private final RedisTemplate&lt;String, Token&gt; tokenRedisTemplate;
        private final RedisTemplate&lt;String, Invoice&gt; invoiceRedisTemplate;
    
        public MyController(
                @Qualifier(&quot;tokenRedisTemplate&quot;) RedisTemplate&lt;String, Token&gt; tokenRedisTemplate,
                @Qualifier(&quot;invoiceRedisTemplate&quot;) RedisTemplate&lt;String, Invoice&gt; invoiceRedisTemplate
        ) {
            this.tokenRedisTemplate = tokenRedisTemplate;
            this.invoiceRedisTemplate = invoiceRedisTemplate;
        }
    
        // Use tokenRedisTemplate and invoiceRedisTemplate in your methods
    
    }

By using the **@Qualifier** annotation along with the respective qualifier names (**tokenRedisTemplate** and **invoiceRedisTemplate**), you can specify which Redis template should be injected in each case. This way, both configurations will coexist, and you&#39;ll be able to use the Redis templates without exceptions.

